</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[806,1421,1728,1903]" pageId="4" pageNumber="853">
<emphasis box="[806,925,1728,1749]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="853">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okada" authorityYear="1968" box="[1228,1345,1728,1749]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Amiota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="853" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuata">
<emphasis box="[1228,1345,1728,1749]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="853">A. sinuata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the shape of the distal part of the paramere, but can be distinguished by the following characters. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okada" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Amiota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="853" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="853">A. sinuata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the distal part of the paramere is slightly longer than the basal part, which is basally not narrowed in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[962,1044,1881,1903]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[164,243,893,912]" captionTargetBox="[326,1280,201,861]" captionTargetId="figure-435@3.[323,1283,197,863]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. Amiota reikae Xu &amp; Chen sp. nov., male terminalia: A, epandrium and cercus; B, surstylus; C, D, hypandrium (hypd), parameres (pm), gonopods (gon; pr, arcuate basal process), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a) (ventral and lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5285874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5285874/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="853">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Chen HW &amp; Toda MJ" box="[1087,1330,1881,1903]" pageId="4" pageNumber="853" pagination="409 - 416" refId="ref6291" refString="Chen HW, Toda MJ. 1998 b. Amiota (Amiota) sinuata species-group, with descriptions of five new species from Southeast Asia (Diptera: Drosophilidae). Journal of Entomological Science 1: 409 - 416." type="journal article" year="1998">Chen &amp; Toda, 1998b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5285880" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5285880" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5285880/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="854" startId="5.[164,243,805,824]" targetBox="[327,1278,198,771]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[164,1442,805,883]" pageId="5" pageNumber="854">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[164,268,805,824]" pageId="5" pageNumber="854">Figure 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Xu &amp; Chen" authorityName="Xu &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2013" box="[279,646,805,824]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Amiota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="854" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesongensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[279,512,805,824]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="854">Amiota hesongensis</emphasis>
Xu &amp; Chen
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[657,743,805,824]" pageId="5" pageNumber="854">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[657,743,805,824]" pageId="5" pageNumber="854" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, male terminalia: A, epandrium and cercus; B, surstylus; C, D, hypandrium (hypd), parameres (pm), gonopods (gon; pr, arcuate basal process), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a) (ventral and lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="5.[164,779,925,1283]" pageId="5" pageNumber="854">
<emphasis box="[164,300,925,946]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="854">Description:</emphasis>
Male. Thorax brownish yellow, with dark-brown patches and stripes; pleura brownish; scutellum yellow, brown on margin. Abdominal tergites black; first to third yellow, medially. Male terminalia: epandrium pubescent except for anterior margin, with about ten setae near posterior margin on each side of the body (
<figureCitation box="[492,577,1108,1130]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[164,243,805,824]" captionTargetBox="[327,1278,198,771]" captionTargetId="figure-460@5.[323,1283,195,774]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Amiota hesongensis Xu &amp; Chen sp. nov., male terminalia: A, epandrium and cercus; B, surstylus; C, D, hypandrium (hypd), parameres (pm), gonopods (gon; pr, arcuate basal process), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a) (ventral and lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5285880" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5285880/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="854">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
). Surstylus with several setae and about nine prensisetae (
<figureCitation box="[681,766,1139,1161]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[164,243,805,824]" captionTargetBox="[327,1278,198,771]" captionTargetId="figure-460@5.[323,1283,195,774]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Amiota hesongensis Xu &amp; Chen sp. nov., male terminalia: A, epandrium and cercus; B, surstylus; C, D, hypandrium (hypd), parameres (pm), gonopods (gon; pr, arcuate basal process), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a) (ventral and lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5285880" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5285880/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="854">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
). Vertical lobe of gonopod broad, arched, slightly sclerotized (
<figureCitation box="[259,344,1200,1222]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[164,243,805,824]" captionTargetBox="[327,1278,198,771]" captionTargetId="figure-460@5.[323,1283,195,774]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Amiota hesongensis Xu &amp; Chen sp. nov., male terminalia: A, epandrium and cercus; B, surstylus; C, D, hypandrium (hypd), parameres (pm), gonopods (gon; pr, arcuate basal process), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a) (ventral and lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5285880" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5285880/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="854">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). Paramere with a row of ~12 sensilla submedially to apically (
<figureCitation box="[455,540,1231,1253]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[164,243,805,824]" captionTargetBox="[327,1278,198,771]" captionTargetId="figure-460@5.[323,1283,195,774]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Amiota hesongensis Xu &amp; Chen sp. nov., male terminalia: A, epandrium and cercus; B, surstylus; C, D, hypandrium (hypd), parameres (pm), gonopods (gon; pr, arcuate basal process), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a) (ventral and lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5285880" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5285880/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="854">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). Aedeagal apodeme longer than wide (
<figureCitation box="[380,465,1261,1283]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[164,243,805,824]" captionTargetBox="[327,1278,198,771]" captionTargetId="figure-460@5.[323,1283,195,774]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Amiota hesongensis Xu &amp; Chen sp. nov., male terminalia: A, epandrium and cercus; B, surstylus; C, D, hypandrium (hypd), parameres (pm), gonopods (gon; pr, arcuate basal process), aedeagus (aed), and aedeagal apodeme (aed a) (ventral and lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5285880" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5285880/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="854">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). Female: unknown.
</paragraph>
